The English translation of the given French sentence is:  "Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War"
SAN FRANCISCO – The invasion of Ukraine by Russia on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a lengthy meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of the Chinese New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a carefully written 5,000-word document announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and has certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free rein to invade and go to war with Ukraine.
He must be very confident and view his confirmation as China's lifetime leader as merely a formality later in the year.
After consolidating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario according to which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin embarked on realizing his lifelong dream with incredible brutality.
As Putin approaches his 70s, he believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, now is the time or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar for them to blindly follow.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, which is emotional to the point of sensibility.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers on multiple occasions when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they are ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the dissolution of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, and then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I became the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tian'anmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise to power very closely, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to nothingness. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Poutine was once a clever operator for the KGB, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out that they were in exactly the same position as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that nothing seems able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into black anger.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deeply rooted corruption in the awarding of defense contracts has also played an important role in its inadequate results.
However, rather than blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally lost his mind.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the electrical network that powers the Chernobyl nuclear plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
It could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already accomplished wonders by managing to reinforce the determination and unity of the EU.
During this time, it seems that Xi realized that Putin is going it alone.
On March 8, one day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remained "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say that he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express the maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will comply with Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
